current status and recent trends

00:08:20.440 --> 00:08:22.030
of the public
transportation industry

00:08:22.030 --> 00:08:27.160
here in the US, what influences
those trends and that status.

00:08:27.160 --> 00:08:30.340
We'll have a critical
assessment of where we are

00:08:30.340 --> 00:08:32.440
and the things that
we'd have to do

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:35.080
to increase the role of
public transportation

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:36.460
if that's what we want.

00:08:36.460 --> 00:08:38.650
We'll talk about
arguments put forth

00:08:38.650 --> 00:08:42.970
in support of public
transport and, in some cases,

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:44.830
rebuttals for them.

00:08:44.830 --> 00:08:47.050
We'll talk what future
influences and ingredients

00:08:47.050 --> 00:08:48.470
for future success.

00:08:48.470 --> 00:08:49.710
Let's get right into it.

00:08:49.710 --> 00:08:53.440
If we look at the transit
industry right now.

00:08:53.440 --> 00:08:59.230
We have ridership patterns that
are increasing but moderately.

00:08:59.230 --> 00:09:00.580
And they remain small.

00:09:00.580 --> 00:09:03.490
Public transportation in
the US and North America

00:09:03.490 --> 00:09:05.800
remains a small percent
of the total mode share.

00:09:05.800 --> 00:09:11.470
Because most people travel
through using private autos

00:09:11.470 --> 00:09:13.600
or modes like that.

00:09:13.600 --> 00:09:15.250
Now, there's a strong
financial support

00:09:15.250 --> 00:09:17.200
from our local
government, local state,

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:21.220
and federal in terms of
funding and providing funding

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:23.710
from tax revenue.

00:09:23.710 --> 00:09:25.270
There has been
significant growth

00:09:25.270 --> 00:09:28.190
in the number of new rail
starts in the past 25 years--

00:09:28.190 --> 00:09:30.880
so new systems, new metro
systems, new light rail

00:09:30.880 --> 00:09:32.260
systems.

00:09:32.260 --> 00:09:33.650
And we'll talk
about why that is,

00:09:33.650 --> 00:09:35.691
that it has to do with
the funding structure here

00:09:35.691 --> 00:09:37.000
in the US.

00:09:37.000 --> 00:09:39.820
There's been also
major rebuilding

00:09:39.820 --> 00:09:40.960
of many older systems.

00:09:40.960 --> 00:09:44.890
And that has to do with the
same funding incentives, which

00:09:44.890 --> 00:09:46.570
is not necessarily
true in Europe

00:09:46.570 --> 00:09:48.190
and other parts of the world.

00:09:48.190 --> 00:09:50.260
Institutional innovation
has been quite slow.

00:09:50.260 --> 00:09:51.670
But there's a
growing recognition

00:09:51.670 --> 00:09:57.970
that, with the new modes of
transportation and where we are

00:09:57.970 --> 00:09:59.740
and where we're going
in terms of trends,

00:09:59.740 --> 00:10:03.160
we might need to rethink some
of that institutional structure.

00:10:03.160 --> 00:10:06.620
And we'll get into that
later in the course.

00:10:06.620 --> 00:10:11.410
So if we look at the
trends in modal split--

00:10:11.410 --> 00:10:16.210
that's one of the first
things that I mentioned--

00:10:16.210 --> 00:10:19.300
over the last,
say, four decades,

00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:25.450
we see that auto is steadily
above 80% in the whole US.

00:10:25.450 --> 00:10:29.140
So it is the dominant
mode for transportation.

00:10:29.140 --> 00:10:30.940
And these are journey to work.

00:10:30.940 --> 00:10:35.440
So this is the morning
commute to work from home.

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:39.478
Transit, on the
other hand, floats

00:10:39.478 --> 00:10:43.640
right around between 2% and
3%, sometimes a bit lower.

00:10:43.640 --> 00:10:46.090
And what we can see
is that in the 1990s--

00:10:46.090 --> 00:10:48.520
in 1990 and 1995--

00:10:48.520 --> 00:10:51.860
you see a slight dip in
public transportation use

00:10:51.860 --> 00:10:55.060
and some increase
in private auto use.

00:10:55.060 --> 00:10:56.800
And since then, we
started a recovery

00:10:56.800 --> 00:11:02.050
towards lower auto use
and slightly higher

00:11:02.050 --> 00:11:04.120
public transportation use.

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:08.350
Walking is the same pattern
as transit and bicycling

00:11:08.350 --> 00:11:08.920
also similar.

00:11:08.920 --> 00:11:10.750
But these are very
small components--

00:11:10.750 --> 00:11:13.240
very, very small modes.

00:11:13.240 --> 00:11:17.330
References for this, if you want
more details, are listed below.

00:11:17.330 --> 00:11:21.050
In terms of ridership
in absolute terms,

00:11:21.050 --> 00:11:23.140
you see that, in the
last four decades,

00:11:23.140 --> 00:11:26.500
we've had an increase,
so especially in rail.

00:11:26.500 --> 00:11:30.500
So if you look at the
dark teal right here,

00:11:30.500 --> 00:11:34.390
