increasing, of course,

00:12:51.120 --> 00:12:52.200
as it always has.

00:12:52.200 --> 00:12:54.607
But especially the urban
population is increasing.

00:12:54.607 --> 00:12:56.940
This happening all around the
world, not just in the US.

00:12:56.940 --> 00:12:59.520
In fact, it's happening
more outside of the US

00:12:59.520 --> 00:13:02.040
than it is here in the US.

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:03.750
If you look at
the UN projections

00:13:03.750 --> 00:13:07.740
for population increase, most
of the population increase

00:13:07.740 --> 00:13:10.860
in the world for
the next decades

00:13:10.860 --> 00:13:14.280
is projected to occur in urban
centers and in Metropolis.

00:13:14.280 --> 00:13:19.930
So in fact, the population
change estimates

00:13:19.930 --> 00:13:22.210
say that rural
population is actually

00:13:22.210 --> 00:13:24.076
going to decrease by 2050.

00:13:24.076 --> 00:13:25.450
So not only are
you going to have

00:13:25.450 --> 00:13:27.460
the natural rate of
population increase

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:30.709
that mostly will
happen in cities,

00:13:30.709 --> 00:13:33.250
you're also going to have people
moving away from rural areas

00:13:33.250 --> 00:13:34.360
into cities.

00:13:34.360 --> 00:13:35.880
And why is that?

00:13:35.880 --> 00:13:37.750
Well, why are people
moving into cities?

00:13:37.750 --> 00:13:40.570
And why is this
happening more and more?

00:13:40.570 --> 00:13:42.057
We have some volunteers?

00:13:42.057 --> 00:13:42.557
Yeah.

00:13:42.557 --> 00:13:45.004
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:45.004 --> 00:13:45.920
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Sure.

00:13:45.920 --> 00:13:50.440
So access to jobs is a big one.

00:13:50.440 --> 00:13:51.508
Yeah.

00:13:51.508 --> 00:13:53.778
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:55.040 --> 00:13:58.010
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: OK,
so it's more than that.

00:13:58.010 --> 00:13:58.510
But yeah.

00:13:58.510 --> 00:14:01.840
So there are more cultural
activities and sports

00:14:01.840 --> 00:14:03.970
and museums and all sorts of--

00:14:03.970 --> 00:14:04.970
MIT.

00:14:04.970 --> 00:14:07.560
So cities-- when we talk
about agglomeration benefits--

00:14:07.560 --> 00:14:08.560
I know we've heard that.

00:14:08.560 --> 00:14:14.180
But cities bring together
health care, education, jobs,

00:14:14.180 --> 00:14:15.830
and people.

00:14:15.830 --> 00:14:18.670
And so when you
live in a place that

00:14:18.670 --> 00:14:20.620
has a high concentration
of these things,

00:14:20.620 --> 00:14:22.420
you have more access
to those things

00:14:22.420 --> 00:14:24.375
than if you were
to live outside.

00:14:24.375 --> 00:14:25.500
And that's true for people.

00:14:25.500 --> 00:14:27.130
It's also true for businesses.

00:14:27.130 --> 00:14:30.610
A business that is looking
to hire talented people

00:14:30.610 --> 00:14:34.930
from universities and have
access to, say, airports

00:14:34.930 --> 00:14:37.540
and other businesses that
provide services to them

00:14:37.540 --> 00:14:42.290
are more likely to find
that in a big city.

00:14:42.290 --> 00:14:45.910
So this is part of what's
fueling these trends.

00:14:45.910 --> 00:14:48.610
And in big cities, we
also have a problem

00:14:48.610 --> 00:14:51.170
because of the high
densities of high traffic.

00:14:51.170 --> 00:14:54.850
So if you're looking at
traveling by private auto,

00:14:54.850 --> 00:14:56.200
you're going to have congestion.

00:14:56.200 --> 00:15:00.700
And in that setting with high
densities and high traffic,

00:15:00.700 --> 00:15:04.870
public transportation becomes
more competitive of a mode.

00:15:04.870 --> 00:15:08.200
But we also have to consider
the negative aspects

00:15:08.200 --> 00:15:10.900
of public transportation from
the passenger's perspective.

00:15:10.900 --> 00:15:12.010
You have to wait.

00:15:12.010 --> 00:15:14.010
It doesn't pick you
up at your door.

00:15:14.010 --> 00:15:16.450
And it doesn't take you right
to the doorstep of where

00:15:16.450 --> 00:15:17.410
you're going to.

00:15:17.410 --> 00:15:18.910
So it's these tradeoffs.

00:15:18.910 --> 00:15:23.260
And when there is enough
traffic and the densities

00:15:23.260 --> 00:15:25.570
are sufficiently high,
then public transportation

00:15:25.570 --> 00:15:28.630
can become very competitive
from a personal decision-making

00:15:28.630 --> 00:15:29.568
standpoint.

00:15:32.320 --> 00:15:34.950
In the US, going back
to the US context--

00:15:34.950 --> 00:15:38.350
and this comes from
the APTA Fact Book.

00:15:38.350 --> 00:15:40.240
They publish this
every few years.

00:15:40.240 --> 00:15:43.930
And they always-- so this
is the 2015 publication

00:15:43.930 --> 00:15:45.530
for two years before that.

00:15:45.530 --> 00:15:50.200
So with data from the American
Community Survey from 2013.

00:15:50.200 --> 00:15:55.240
And if we rank the
sort of largest US

00:15:55.240 --> 00:16:00.070
cities and metropolitan
areas really by size

00:16:00.070 --> 00:16:05.350
and then we look at
their transit mode share,

00:16:05.350 --> 00:16:06.290
this is what we get.

00:16:06.290 --> 00:16:09.220
So the biggest one,
by far, in the US

00:16:09.220 --> 00:16:12.087
is the New York
metropolitan area.

00:16:12.087 --> 00:16:14.420
And right below that, we have
San Francisco, Washington,

00:16:14.420 --> 00:16:16.820
Boston, Chicago, Philadelphia.

00:16:16.820 --> 00:16:20.860
And then you start seeing a
decrease and a pretty rapid

00:16:20.860 --> 00:16:23.620
decrease in the
percent of workers

00:16:23.620 --> 00:16:27.820
in those metropolises that use
transit to commute to work.

00:16:27.820 --> 00:16:35.590
So the question is, why is
the mode share so much higher

00:16:35.590 --> 00:16:38.230
for these first few cities?

00:16:38.230 --> 00:16:40.790
What do those cities
have in common

00:16:40.790 --> 00:16:43.744
that the cities below
them don't have?

00:16:43.744 --> 00:16:46.410
AUDIENCE: They have
an old rail structure.

00:16:46.410 --> 00:16:49.530
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: OK,
so that's a good idea.

00:16:49.530 --> 00:16:50.920
Yeah.

00:16:50.920 --> 00:16:51.450
Over here.

00:16:51.450 --> 00:16:52.840
AUDIENCE: I mean, they have
very, very high population

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:53.680
densities.

00:16:53.680 --> 00:16:56.077
New York is like 70,000
people per square mile

00:16:56.077 --> 00:16:58.250
and Dallas is
probably like three.

00:16:58.250 --> 00:16:59.330
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: OK.

00:16:59.330 --> 00:17:01.490
AUDIENCE: They have
expensive downtown parking.

00:17:01.490 --> 00:17:03.400
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Yes.

00:17:03.400 --> 00:17:04.930
Other ideas?

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:07.746
AUDIENCE: They're
all older cities.

00:17:07.746 --> 00:17:09.829
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: And it's
also related to the fact

00:17:09.829 --> 00:17:11.250
that you have older systems.

00:17:11.250 --> 00:17:13.970
So in fact, those first few--
those first six that I've

00:17:13.970 --> 00:17:17.329
mentioned, say New York
through Philadelphia--

00:17:17.329 --> 00:17:22.650
are the oldest
systems in the US.

00:17:22.650 --> 00:17:23.420
DC is newer.

00:17:23.420 --> 00:17:24.319
That's right.

00:17:24.319 --> 00:17:32.970
But most of the ones below them
are newer, even newer than DC.

00:17:32.970 --> 00:17:38.310
So these are cities that
had an urban fabric that

00:17:38.310 --> 00:17:41.490
was created and
developed and densified

00:17:41.490 --> 00:17:44.820
before the US road
infrastructure was developed

00:17:44.820 --> 00:17:45.990
as it is today.

00:17:45.990 --> 00:17:50.610
And therefore, the densities
developed at a higher level.

00:17:50.610 --> 00:17:53.520
And they already had
public transportation

00:17:53.520 --> 00:17:57.540
serving those sort of OD
pairs in those cities.

00:17:57.540 --> 00:18:00.810
So it's sort of a
cyclical virtuous

00:18:00.810 --> 00:18:03.630
cycle that sort of makes
public transportation

00:18:03.630 --> 00:18:06.300
at those places more
efficient and more

00:18:06.300 --> 00:18:10.039
competitive than
the private auto.

00:18:10.039 --> 00:18:11.080
Any questions about that?

00:18:16.810 --> 00:18:21.700
If we look at so the
transit share modal split

00:18:21.700 --> 00:18:24.280
for home-to-work journeys,
this is a little older.

00:18:24.280 --> 00:18:25.960
This is a study
that was completed

00:18:25.960 --> 00:18:29.320
with data from the year 2000.

00:18:29.320 --> 00:18:31.070
And we have different
numbers here.

00:18:31.070 --> 00:18:35.950
But I just want to focus on
these five biggest public

00:18:35.950 --> 00:18:39.100
transportation
systems or big cities.

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:45.100
And we see the mode share
in each of them for a car

00:18:45.100 --> 00:18:49.660
and for transit in 2000
and transit in 2013.

00:18:49.660 --> 00:18:54.390
So we can see that, although
in Chicago it mostly

00:18:54.390 --> 00:18:57.910
has stayed around the
same, in New York and San

00:18:57.910 --> 00:19:00.790
Francisco and Washington and
Boston, it has increased.

00:19:00.790 --> 00:19:03.940
So there's been an increase
in the transit mode share.

00:19:03.940 --> 00:19:06.520
Population has increased
in these cities

00:19:06.520 --> 00:19:08.690
and so has the public
transportation mode share.

00:19:11.640 --> 00:19:14.580
In terms of public
transportation funding.

00:19:14.580 --> 00:19:17.670
So how will these systems
that are expensive to run

00:19:17.670 --> 00:19:18.420
get funded--

00:19:18.420 --> 00:19:20.230
and expensive to
build get funded?

00:19:20.230 --> 00:19:23.340
So the first thing to note
is that, in North America,

00:19:23.340 --> 00:19:26.520
there's a tradition of
dividing the expenses

00:19:26.520 --> 00:19:28.600
and the expenditures of
public transportation

00:19:28.600 --> 00:19:31.770
into capital expenditures
and operational expenditures.

00:19:31.770 --> 00:19:34.650
That's not true
elsewhere in the world.

00:19:34.650 --> 00:19:36.160
But it is in North America.

00:19:36.160 --> 00:19:37.980
So when we talk about
capital expenditures,

00:19:37.980 --> 00:19:39.810
we're talking about
building new systems,

00:19:39.810 --> 00:19:42.930
extending systems,
procuring new vehicles,

00:19:42.930 --> 00:19:47.400
rolling stock, repairs,
and things like that.

00:19:47.400 --> 00:19:51.260
Operating expenses
are what you used

00:19:51.260 --> 00:19:55.560
to pay salaries of
drivers, pay for energy

00:19:55.560 --> 00:20:00.480
or fuel to propel the
vehicles forward, et cetera.

00:20:00.480 --> 00:20:03.900
So another thing to
note is that, if we

00:20:03.900 --> 00:20:07.590
look at operating expenses
for example, about a third

00:20:07.590 --> 00:20:10.590
of the operating expenses
are covered by fares.

00:20:10.590 --> 00:20:12.360
So when you use
the system and you

00:20:12.360 --> 00:20:15.630
pay for it and you pay your
$2 or whatever it costs,

00:20:15.630 --> 00:20:17.310
you're only paying
for about a third

00:20:17.310 --> 00:20:20.250
of what it costs the system to
provide that journey for you

00:20:20.250 --> 00:20:21.710
on average.

00:20:21.710 --> 00:20:24.000
It does vary from
system to system.

00:20:24.000 --> 00:20:29.170
And in some parts of the world,
these numbers are different.

00:20:29.170 --> 00:20:33.250
When we talk about local, state,
and federal support or funding,

00:20:33.250 --> 00:20:35.630
this all comes
from tax revenues.

00:20:35.630 --> 00:20:37.870
So this could be sales
tax, especially when we're

00:20:37.870 --> 00:20:41.290
talking about local and state,
and federal taxes, mostly

00:20:41.290 --> 00:20:42.070
income taxes.

00:20:45.720 --> 00:20:48.120
In terms of capital
expenditures,

00:20:48.120 --> 00:20:50.670
what I want to highlight
is that the federal support

00:20:50.670 --> 00:20:53.000
is quite high, more than 40%.

00:20:53.000 --> 00:20:55.020
And that's much higher
for capital expenditures

00:20:55.020 --> 00:20:57.240
than it is for
operating expenditures.

00:20:57.240 --> 00:20:59.850
What would that encourage
if you're a state

00:20:59.850 --> 00:21:02.505
or you're an agency
and you're operating

00:21:02.505 --> 00:21:05.700
a public transportation agency
and you get a lot of subsidy

00:21:05.700 --> 00:21:07.330
from the federal level--

00:21:07.330 --> 00:21:11.460
so not necessarily
your constituents

00:21:11.460 --> 00:21:14.820
for capital expenditures, but
not operating expenditures.

00:21:14.820 --> 00:21:18.275
What would that
encourage you to do?

00:21:18.275 --> 00:21:20.175
AUDIENCE: Build more
and maintain less?

00:21:20.175 --> 00:21:22.360
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Build
more and maintain less.

00:21:22.360 --> 00:21:24.460
That's exactly right.

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:27.820
So remember I said
earlier there's

00:21:27.820 --> 00:21:31.550
been a lot of new builds
in the last 25 years

00:21:31.550 --> 00:21:34.550
and a of major repairs
in the last 20 years?

00:21:34.550 --> 00:21:37.750
This is why, because there's
a lot of federal support

00:21:37.750 --> 00:21:39.850
for doing those projects.

00:21:39.850 --> 00:21:42.940
And unfortunately, you
build a bigger system

00:21:42.940 --> 00:21:44.530
and you have to now run it.

00:21:44.530 --> 00:21:46.610
And that comes from
operating expenses,

00:21:46.610 --> 00:21:48.190
which are not as
strongly supported

00:21:48.190 --> 00:21:49.790
by the federal government.

00:21:49.790 --> 00:21:53.991
So that also hints at
maybe why the industry

00:21:53.991 --> 00:21:55.990
is where it is in terms
of state of grid repair.

00:21:58.890 --> 00:22:01.380
What influences these trends?

00:22:01.380 --> 00:22:04.620
First one, and the very
obvious, is the suburbanization

00:22:04.620 --> 00:22:06.390
of homes, employment,
and attractors.

00:22:06.390 --> 00:22:11.310
People moving away from
cities to lower dense areas.

00:22:11.310 --> 00:22:14.070
Because property is cheaper
and parking might be free.

00:22:16.890 --> 00:22:20.730
In America, low costs for
car ownership and operation.

00:22:20.730 --> 00:22:24.450
So we have low fuel
taxes in comparison

00:22:24.450 --> 00:22:28.830
to other parts of the world and
low taxes when you buy cars.

00:22:28.830 --> 00:22:31.260
There is an extensive
urban road infrastructure

00:22:31.260 --> 00:22:35.677
that is much higher than it is
in other parts of the world.

00:22:35.677 --> 00:22:37.260
And there are many
government policies

00:22:37.260 --> 00:22:45.130
that sort of support the road
construction and maintenance

00:22:45.130 --> 00:22:47.190
and the use of roads and
the private automobile

00:22:47.190 --> 00:22:49.320
and not necessarily
to the same extent

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:51.090
support public transportation.

00:22:51.090 --> 00:22:54.210
These include things
like tax benefits

00:22:54.210 --> 00:22:56.730
that you can take on your
return, parking requirements

00:22:56.730 --> 00:23:00.810
when there is new
construction that, again,

00:23:00.810 --> 00:23:03.210
support the private auto.

00:23:03.210 --> 00:23:04.680
If we look at
suburbanization just

00:23:04.680 --> 00:23:07.680
focusing on the first point and
looking at the same data set

00:23:07.680 --> 00:23:09.929
I talked about earlier,
the 2000 journey to work,

00:23:09.929 --> 00:23:11.220
we have different numbers here.

00:23:11.220 --> 00:23:14.800
But what I really want to
focus on is we have here--

00:23:14.800 --> 00:23:17.190
this is like an OD matrix
but by part of the city.

00:23:17.190 --> 00:23:22.050
So if you live in the
central city or a suburb

00:23:22.050 --> 00:23:26.040
and you work in the
central city or suburb,

00:23:26.040 --> 00:23:29.130
what percent of total trips
are covered by each mode?

00:23:29.130 --> 00:23:36.750
So we see that we have about 27%
of trips are from central city

00:23:36.750 --> 00:23:38.250
to central city.

00:23:38.250 --> 00:23:43.170
And about 20% are from the
suburbs to the central city,

00:23:43.170 --> 00:23:45.930
so people commuting inbound to
the central business district

00:23:45.930 --> 00:23:47.430
in the traditional sense.

00:23:47.430 --> 00:23:51.030
Then there's the reverse
commuters, about 9%,

00:23:51.030 --> 00:23:54.990
who are living in
the central city

00:23:54.990 --> 00:23:57.220
and commuting outbound
into the suburbs.

00:23:57.220 --> 00:23:59.422
And then there is
the suburb to suburb,

00:23:59.422 --> 00:24:01.630
people who live in the suburb
and work in the suburb,

00:24:01.630 --> 00:24:04.450
not necessarily in
the same suburb.

00:24:04.450 --> 00:24:07.230
OK, so that's interesting.

00:24:07.230 --> 00:24:10.140
That's how the trips are made.

00:24:10.140 --> 00:24:12.300
What happens if we
look at the increase?

00:24:12.300 --> 00:24:16.780
What are the trends from 1990 to
2000 leading to these numbers?

00:24:16.780 --> 00:24:19.500
Well, by far, the
biggest increase

00:24:19.500 --> 00:24:23.320
was in suburb-to-suburb
commutes.

00:24:23.320 --> 00:24:28.380
And if we look at the public
transportation mode share,

00:24:28.380 --> 00:24:31.620
if you live in the city and work
in the city, about 14% of trips

00:24:31.620 --> 00:24:36.330
are covered, are made by
public transportation.

00:24:36.330 --> 00:24:36.900
It's lower.

00:24:36.900 --> 00:24:39.750
It's about 6% if you're
going to or from the suburb.

00:24:39.750 --> 00:24:42.480
And it's much lower, 2%,
if you live in the suburbs

00:24:42.480 --> 00:24:43.680
and work in the suburbs.

00:24:43.680 --> 00:24:47.280
So if you just focus
on three numbers here.

00:24:47.280 --> 00:24:53.340
43% of trips are from
a suburb to a suburb.

00:24:53.340 --> 00:24:55.500
The trend is that
suburb-to-suburb trips

00:24:55.500 --> 00:24:56.700
are increasing.

00:24:56.700 --> 00:25:00.210
And that is the
hardest thing to serve

00:25:00.210 --> 00:25:01.730
with public transportation.

00:25:04.260 --> 00:25:04.940
Why is that?

00:25:04.940 --> 00:25:07.250
Why is it difficult
to serve those trips

00:25:07.250 --> 00:25:09.166
with public transportation?

00:25:09.166 --> 00:25:11.080
AUDIENCE: Low density?

00:25:11.080 --> 00:25:12.870
GABRIEL SANCHEZ:
Why is low density--

00:25:12.870 --> 00:25:16.500
why does that make it
difficult to serve--

00:25:16.500 --> 00:25:18.900
AUDIENCE: Because then it's--

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:20.820
people that need
access to stations,

00:25:20.820 --> 00:25:22.740
they're not [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:26.110 --> 00:25:28.750
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Well, you
could put more service.

00:25:28.750 --> 00:25:30.530
You could put more bus
stops and stations.

00:25:30.530 --> 00:25:31.365
So--

00:25:31.365 --> 00:25:33.198
AUDIENCE: But then
there's not enough people

00:25:33.198 --> 00:25:35.010
to take it to make it
financially viable.

00:25:35.010 --> 00:25:36.051
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Exactly.

00:25:36.051 --> 00:25:38.660
So did you hear that?

00:25:38.660 --> 00:25:40.190
So because you have
low densities--

00:25:40.190 --> 00:25:44.271
you have a sparse OD matrix,
as we say in transportation.

00:25:44.271 --> 00:25:45.770
You have fewer
people that are going

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:49.180
from any particular origin to
any particular destination.

00:25:49.180 --> 00:25:51.260
When you don't have
those critical densities,

00:25:51.260 --> 00:25:54.170
it becomes very expensive
and very inefficient

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:56.930
to deploy resources to
move a lot of people

00:25:56.930 --> 00:26:01.200
when the demand for moving a
lot of people is not there.

00:26:01.200 --> 00:26:04.610
On the other hand, when you
have dense corridors along which

00:26:04.610 --> 00:26:09.080
many people want to move, you do
develop this competitive demand

00:26:09.080 --> 00:26:12.110
pattern that is very well
served by public transportation.

00:26:12.110 --> 00:26:15.410
And it's very correlated with
whether you are in the suburbs

