OK.

00:29:31.580 --> 00:29:35.360
So here in the US, coming
back, especially to the North

00:29:35.360 --> 00:29:39.260
American context, we
have our car road system.

00:29:39.260 --> 00:29:42.470
So very highly developed,
more than in other parts

00:29:42.470 --> 00:29:45.470
of the world.

00:29:45.470 --> 00:29:46.550
Many people own cars.

00:29:46.550 --> 00:29:49.650
There are 600 cars for
every 1,000 people.

00:29:49.650 --> 00:29:51.510
The car usage is high.

00:29:51.510 --> 00:29:52.800
If you look at the--

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:57.110
it's 10,000 vehicle kilometers
per person per year.

00:29:57.110 --> 00:29:59.310
Compared to other countries,
we have lower taxes,

00:29:59.310 --> 00:30:01.610
lower fees, lower user charges.

00:30:01.610 --> 00:30:05.870
So sales taxes are 5% to 8%.

00:30:05.870 --> 00:30:09.410
Users pay for only about 60%
of the road infrastructure.

00:30:09.410 --> 00:30:11.390
That comes from tolls
and from gas taxes.

00:30:14.190 --> 00:30:17.310
The fuel taxes here in
the US are 10% to 20%

00:30:17.310 --> 00:30:18.520
of what they are in Europe.

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:20.730
So it gives you an
idea of where we are

00:30:20.730 --> 00:30:23.880
and why our policies
encourage owning a car

00:30:23.880 --> 00:30:26.790
and operating a car.

00:30:26.790 --> 00:30:28.129
Parking is another big one.

00:30:28.129 --> 00:30:29.170
I already mentioned this.

00:30:29.170 --> 00:30:32.790
So the parking supply
in most of the US

00:30:32.790 --> 00:30:35.250
is free and widely available.

00:30:35.250 --> 00:30:39.850
So there are 380 parking spaces
per 1,000 central city workers

00:30:39.850 --> 00:30:41.250
in the 10 largest cities.

00:30:41.250 --> 00:30:42.769
Outside of that,
it's much higher.

00:30:42.769 --> 00:30:43.560
Everybody can park.

00:30:43.560 --> 00:30:46.470
About 95% of car commuters
enjoy free parking.

00:30:46.470 --> 00:30:50.400
So if it doesn't cost you to own
a car or to operate it and you

00:30:50.400 --> 00:30:54.360
can park free-- you can leave
your piece of metal doing

00:30:54.360 --> 00:30:58.650
nothing and taking up real
estate in a city with no cost--

00:30:58.650 --> 00:31:00.460
then you might go
ahead and do that.

00:31:00.460 --> 00:31:04.940
So it's a highly developed
urban road system.

00:31:04.940 --> 00:31:08.420
We have more roads,
wider roads, longer roads

00:31:08.420 --> 00:31:11.010
than in other
parts of the world,

00:31:11.010 --> 00:31:14.270
especially if we compare Europe.

00:31:14.270 --> 00:31:17.220
And we're talking here about
the 10 largest cities in the US.

00:31:17.220 --> 00:31:18.770
We're not talking
about rural areas.

00:31:21.280 --> 00:31:24.120
What do people say when
they're advocating for transit?

00:31:24.120 --> 00:31:25.660
What are the
traditional arguments

00:31:25.660 --> 00:31:28.720
put forth for transit
being good and therefore

00:31:28.720 --> 00:31:31.130
we should support transit,
we should fund transit?

00:31:31.130 --> 00:31:32.630
The equity is a big one.

00:31:32.630 --> 00:31:39.310
So access for people who cannot
drive or choose not to drive.

00:31:39.310 --> 00:31:42.160
So we're talking about
elderly, handicapped,

00:31:42.160 --> 00:31:46.690
children who can't
drive, poor people

00:31:46.690 --> 00:31:48.520
who can't afford to
buy their own car

00:31:48.520 --> 00:31:51.170
or to use modes like
Uber, for example.

00:31:51.170 --> 00:31:52.420
So that's the equity argument.

00:31:52.420 --> 00:31:55.090
And that's a very
sound argument.

00:31:55.090 --> 00:31:55.880
Congestion.

00:31:55.880 --> 00:31:58.210
So people say put
public transportation

00:31:58.210 --> 00:32:00.070
to alleviate congestion.

00:32:00.070 --> 00:32:03.490
That's not such a good argument
because lots of the studies

00:32:03.490 --> 00:32:06.190
that we've looked at,
even when a lot of people

00:32:06.190 --> 00:32:08.980
do take public transportation
when a new system is put in,

00:32:08.980 --> 00:32:11.680
the capacity released
in the streets

00:32:11.680 --> 00:32:12.910
is usually very quickly.

00:32:15.540 --> 00:32:17.290
They demand it again.

00:32:17.290 --> 00:32:20.950
So that is not a very
effective method, by itself,

00:32:20.950 --> 00:32:22.270
for reducing congestion.

00:32:22.270 --> 00:32:26.350
If you tie it to other things
like parking taxes or parking

00:32:26.350 --> 00:32:31.060
caps or tolls, then
with a combination

00:32:31.060 --> 00:32:33.850
of an increase in public
transportation supply

00:32:33.850 --> 00:32:38.230
and an increase in cost or
disutility for taking the car,

00:32:38.230 --> 00:32:40.120
you can have an
impact on congestion.

00:32:40.120 --> 00:32:41.270
Land use.

00:32:41.270 --> 00:32:45.580
So if you want a
nicer, walkable city,

00:32:45.580 --> 00:32:48.160
then you should have
public transportation.

00:32:48.160 --> 00:32:50.380
If you're driving your
car from home to work,

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:52.030
you're not going to stop.

00:32:52.030 --> 00:32:53.740
You're going to work.

00:32:53.740 --> 00:32:55.960
And so when you're taking
public transportation

00:32:55.960 --> 00:33:00.010
and you stop along
dense corridors

00:33:00.010 --> 00:33:02.890
and you probably won't get
dropped off immediately

00:33:02.890 --> 00:33:06.130
where you're going to so you
might have to walk by stores

00:33:06.130 --> 00:33:08.830
and by restaurants,
that's going to generate

00:33:08.830 --> 00:33:09.970
commercial activity.

00:33:09.970 --> 00:33:15.520
And it's going to support a land
use that is of nicer quality

00:33:15.520 --> 00:33:18.460
than the car might do by itself.

00:33:18.460 --> 00:33:19.270
Environmental.

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:24.120
So if people say, let's put
public transportation in

00:33:24.120 --> 00:33:25.970
because it's good
for the environment.

00:33:25.970 --> 00:33:28.800
Well, it turns out
that actually it's

00:33:28.800 --> 00:33:33.210
more effective to work
on the car technology--

00:33:33.210 --> 00:33:35.090
hybrid cars, fuel efficiency.

00:33:35.090 --> 00:33:38.550
It's a much more effective way
to help the environment just

00:33:38.550 --> 00:33:41.260
because so many people drive.

00:33:41.260 --> 00:33:43.410
The mode split is so much.

00:33:43.410 --> 00:33:46.990
It's about 80% for a car.

00:33:46.990 --> 00:33:52.640
It makes a bigger dent to
work on car energy efficiency.

00:33:52.640 --> 00:33:54.050
Same with energy.

00:33:54.050 --> 00:33:56.030
It has to do with
the same things.

00:33:56.030 --> 00:33:56.960
OK, other arguments.

00:33:56.960 --> 00:33:59.000
So economic expenditures
for private autos

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:02.930
may be used to improve local
economies and quality of life.

00:34:02.930 --> 00:34:07.670
So we say we subsidize
the private auto.

00:34:07.670 --> 00:34:09.710
Because people, through
their user fees,

00:34:09.710 --> 00:34:12.530
are only paying for
about 60% of the costs.

00:34:12.530 --> 00:34:15.949
The remaining cost is
coming from tax revenue that

00:34:15.949 --> 00:34:18.650
could have been spent on
nicer cities and nicer

00:34:18.650 --> 00:34:21.449
public transportation systems.

00:34:21.449 --> 00:34:23.340
And then there's the
agglomeration benefits.

00:34:23.340 --> 00:34:25.920
If you want to increase
the economic activity

00:34:25.920 --> 00:34:28.949
and the socioeconomic
welfare of a city,

00:34:28.949 --> 00:34:30.600
then you can put in
transit because it

00:34:30.600 --> 00:34:32.340
supports higher densities.

00:34:32.340 --> 00:34:35.909
So how would New York and
Boston and San Francisco

00:34:35.909 --> 00:34:39.150
be or have developed
if they didn't

00:34:39.150 --> 00:34:42.582
have their public transportation
systems right now?

00:34:42.582 --> 00:34:44.790
They really would be nothing
like they are right now.

00:34:44.790 --> 00:34:48.270
If you took Manhattan and
shut down all the metros--

00:34:48.270 --> 00:34:51.060
and we've had these real-life
experiments when hurricanes

00:34:51.060 --> 00:34:52.170
come around--

00:34:52.170 --> 00:34:53.850
the city shuts down.

00:34:53.850 --> 00:34:57.480
You can't commute into the
city without these systems.

00:34:57.480 --> 00:34:59.700
There is not enough
capacity on the roads

00:34:59.700 --> 00:35:02.770
to bringing all those people
in and to support that economy.

00:35:02.770 --> 00:35:06.270
So there is a benefit to
having these systems in.

00:35:06.270 --> 00:35:09.270
But because these investments
were made sometimes

00:35:09.270 --> 00:35:12.970
a century ago, nobody
is talking about

00:35:12.970 --> 00:35:17.650
or quantifying the benefit in
assigning it to that system.

00:35:17.650 --> 00:35:19.720
So the contribution of
earlier investments,

00:35:19.720 --> 00:35:22.230
especially in heavy rail,
is not being valued.

00:35:22.230 --> 00:35:24.550
That has changed a
little bit recently.

00:35:24.550 --> 00:35:27.810
So when London was doing
its economic analysis

00:35:27.810 --> 00:35:31.200
for Crossrail, a big metro
system across the city,

00:35:31.200 --> 00:35:33.270
they did say, we
need a long view.

00:35:33.270 --> 00:35:38.430
This is going to have benefits
lasting many, many decades.

00:35:38.430 --> 00:35:40.410
We're not looking at
a 20, 30-year horizon.

00:35:40.410 --> 00:35:42.120
We're looking at
way beyond that.

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:44.700
We want London to prosper
and to become more dense

00:35:44.700 --> 00:35:48.660
and to have higher
agglomeration benefits.

00:35:48.660 --> 00:35:51.840
So other arguments
are that transit

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:55.380
decreases the external costs
of transportation in cities.

00:35:55.380 --> 00:35:57.540
So when we look at
things like accidents,

00:35:57.540 --> 00:35:59.835
you're less likely to be
to get into an accident

00:35:59.835 --> 00:36:04.380
if you're in a bus than
if you are driving a car.

00:36:04.380 --> 00:36:06.390
Impacts on human health.

00:36:06.390 --> 00:36:10.695
Any clue about what
I mean by that?

00:36:10.695 --> 00:36:11.564
AUDIENCE: Walking.

00:36:11.564 --> 00:36:12.480
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: Yeah.

00:36:12.480 --> 00:36:12.980
Walking.

00:36:12.980 --> 00:36:14.240
So you walk a little more.

00:36:14.240 --> 00:36:14.740
Yeah.

00:36:18.650 --> 00:36:22.760
There's the impact of if
you have a lot of traffic

00:36:22.760 --> 00:36:24.470
and you're sort of
sitting in traffic,

00:36:24.470 --> 00:36:27.200
you're breathing in dirty air.

00:36:27.200 --> 00:36:30.860
So if that's the case,
pollution kills people slowly

00:36:30.860 --> 00:36:34.640
but at a higher rate than
accidents and other things.

00:36:34.640 --> 00:36:37.700
So these are the
impacts on human health.

00:36:37.700 --> 00:36:40.940
And I did say earlier that
public transportation by itself

00:36:40.940 --> 00:36:42.590
is not going to address that.

00:36:42.590 --> 00:36:45.890
But if you pair it
with some policy that

00:36:45.890 --> 00:36:50.180
will curb the private auto
demand and reduce emissions,

00:36:50.180 --> 00:36:53.164
then you can have an
impact on health care,

00:36:53.164 --> 00:36:54.830
healthier costs from
the government side

00:36:54.830 --> 00:36:58.350
and the human health for people.

00:36:58.350 --> 00:37:02.000
So again, congestion, noise.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:06.800
We can reduce the noise
of cars on streets.

00:37:06.800 --> 00:37:10.430
And climate change,
global warming.

00:37:10.430 --> 00:37:15.460
Here's a nice picture of public
transportation catalyzing

00:37:15.460 --> 00:37:17.110
sort of the urban fabric.

00:37:17.110 --> 00:37:19.630
So making cities
more walkable just

00:37:19.630 --> 00:37:23.297
to highlight what
we said earlier.

00:37:23.297 --> 00:37:24.130
Critical assessment.

00:37:24.130 --> 00:37:27.610
So we've stabilized public
transport in North America.

00:37:27.610 --> 00:37:31.150
We saw that, in
the 1990s, we had

00:37:31.150 --> 00:37:33.130
an increase in the
mode share of auto

00:37:33.130 --> 00:37:35.050
and a decrease in public
transport and walking

00:37:35.050 --> 00:37:35.830
and biking.

00:37:35.830 --> 00:37:39.459
And now, that's starting
to come back up.

00:37:39.459 --> 00:37:41.500
There are many new rail
initiatives like Phoenix,

00:37:41.500 --> 00:37:42.624
Denver, and Salt Lake City.

00:37:42.624 --> 00:37:44.410
And they are successful.

00:37:44.410 --> 00:37:47.110
And especially if we look at
older systems like New York

00:37:47.110 --> 00:37:49.600
City but also at some of the
not-so-old ones like Houston

00:37:49.600 --> 00:37:53.080
and Seattle, we see
very successful systems

00:37:53.080 --> 00:37:55.240
that are being
heavily used and are

00:37:55.240 --> 00:38:01.030
contributing to nicer land use
and developing the economy.

00:38:01.030 --> 00:38:03.610
Institutional change is
occurring very slowly, maybe

00:38:03.610 --> 00:38:05.260
too slowly.

00:38:05.260 --> 00:38:08.390
Many things are changing
in terms of technology,

00:38:08.390 --> 00:38:10.090
in terms of policy,
in terms of what

00:38:10.090 --> 00:38:12.060
the private sector is offering.

00:38:12.060 --> 00:38:15.590
And the public sector
is not catching up.

00:38:15.590 --> 00:38:17.210
It's not moving as quickly.

00:38:17.210 --> 00:38:20.930
So another challenge is the
retention of political support.

00:38:20.930 --> 00:38:22.690
So yes, question here.

00:38:22.690 --> 00:38:24.485
AUDIENCE: This is
just North America?

00:38:24.485 --> 00:38:26.610
GABRIEL SANCHEZ: This is
focusing in North America.

00:38:26.610 --> 00:38:27.430
AUDIENCE: Because
China, for example,

00:38:27.430 --> 00:38:29.221
is building a crazy
amount of [INAUDIBLE]..

00:38:29.221 --> 00:38:31.780
GABRIEL SANCHEZ:
But they also have

00:38:31.780 --> 00:38:34.110
a big increase in private auto.

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:36.420
So both things are happening.

00:38:40.170 --> 00:38:43.590
So retention of political
support is another challenge.

00:38:43.590 --> 00:38:49.320
So just keeping everyone happy
and having those stakeholders

00:38:49.320 --> 00:38:53.430
in a political
constituency happy enough

00:38:53.430 --> 00:38:57.870
to support you and
not try to defund

00:38:57.870 --> 00:39:00.030
the public
transportation sector.

00:39:00.030 --> 00:39:05.340
Especially-- that's critical
if public interpretation

00:39:05.340 --> 00:39:08.190
is much better at serving
the most dense corridors

00:39:08.190 --> 00:39:10.710
and you're only
benefiting people there.

00:39:10.710 --> 00:39:13.890
And people from, for example,
the rest of the state

00:39:13.890 --> 00:39:15.630
don't see a direct benefit.

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:18.600
But they're putting sales
tax into that system.

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:21.480
That's a tricky
thing politically.

00:39:21.480 --> 00:39:24.030
So that's another challenge.

00:39:24.030 --> 00:39:28.570
So we expect to see continued
growth in the periphery.

00:39:28.570 --> 00:39:31.371
So suburbanization.

00:39:31.371 --> 00:39:32.620
Health care is getting better.

00:39:32.620 --> 00:39:35.910
So the percent of people
that are old and can't drive

00:39:35.910 --> 00:39:37.270
is going up.

00:39:37.270 --> 00:39:39.240
And so that might
mean that we might

00:39:39.240 --> 00:39:41.320
need more public transport.

00:39:41.320 --> 00:39:43.150
Technology is changing.

00:39:43.150 --> 00:39:46.300
Telecommunications is
advancing rapidly now

00:39:46.300 --> 00:39:49.870
with all the internet of
things and sensors everywhere.

00:39:49.870 --> 00:39:51.230
We do get a lot of data.

00:39:51.230 --> 00:39:54.732
And we can start using that
data to plan better systems

00:39:54.732 --> 00:39:56.440
and to analyze how
people are using them.

00:39:56.440 --> 00:39:59.900
And we'll get to that
later in this course.

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:04.330
The public has a
higher expectation.

00:40:04.330 --> 00:40:05.980
Because you have a
smartphone and you

00:40:05.980 --> 00:40:08.560
can know where the
bus is, you sort of

00:40:08.560 --> 00:40:10.780
are more aware of the system.

00:40:10.780 --> 00:40:13.330
And you might start to demand
higher quality service.

00:40:13.330 --> 00:40:16.090
And if other parts of the world
or other systems are doing it

00:40:16.090 --> 00:40:20.020
and mine isn't, then I'm
starting to expect that--

00:40:20.020 --> 00:40:23.710
I know about it because we
share all of this information

00:40:23.710 --> 00:40:25.580
through YouTube
and the internet.

00:40:25.580 --> 00:40:28.000
So I want the same
thing in my city.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.650
And I want the same
thing in my system.

00:40:30.650 --> 00:40:32.290
And then finally--
and this is very

00:40:32.290 --> 00:40:34.660
recent-- the transportation
network company.

00:40:34.660 --> 00:40:39.090
So the likes of Uber and
Lyft are making a dent

00:40:39.090 --> 00:40:41.590
on the demand and
the mobile split.

00:40:41.590 --> 00:40:44.710
So this is somewhere in between
where it's not your own auto

00:40:44.710 --> 00:40:46.690
and you're paying for something.

00:40:46.690 --> 00:40:49.540
You might be carpooling so
in some sense it's public,

00:40:49.540 --> 00:40:50.230
but not really.

00:40:50.230 --> 00:40:53.590
So the other challenge
here is that a lot of these

00:40:53.590 --> 00:40:57.790
are startups that are heavily
funded by venture capital.

00:40:57.790 --> 00:41:01.540
And they are spending more
money than they can make

00:41:01.540 --> 00:41:03.970
through their fair revenues.

00:41:03.970 --> 00:41:08.680
So it's not clear how that will
play out as the years go by

00:41:08.680 --> 00:41:10.120
and if they can
keep their prices

00:41:10.120 --> 00:41:13.750
and remain as competitive.

00:41:13.750 --> 00:41:16.070
So ingredients for
future success.

00:41:16.070 --> 00:41:20.590
So again, speaking of the
political constituencies,

00:41:20.590 --> 00:41:23.020
maintaining a
supportive coalition.

00:41:23.020 --> 00:41:27.280
So making sure that you
expand that base of people

00:41:27.280 --> 00:41:28.900
who benefit from
public transport

00:41:28.900 --> 00:41:31.360
and make the case that,
even if you're not directly

00:41:31.360 --> 00:41:35.350
using public transportation, it
has economic benefit for you.

00:41:35.350 --> 00:41:40.420
So that's necessary if we want
to move forward, especially

00:41:40.420 --> 00:41:44.950
with the government funding
local and state taxes

00:41:44.950 --> 00:41:47.780
for example for
public transportation.

00:41:47.780 --> 00:41:50.050
Expand the definition
of public transport.

00:41:50.050 --> 00:41:53.860
There is now a greater
variety of services

00:41:53.860 --> 00:41:55.270
and more flexibility.

00:41:55.270 --> 00:41:58.550
And public
transportation systems

00:41:58.550 --> 00:42:02.910
are starting to consider
different vehicle sizes

00:42:02.910 --> 00:42:05.010
and partnering with
transportation network

00:42:05.010 --> 00:42:11.190
companies to achieve
higher efficiencies

00:42:11.190 --> 00:42:17.880
and just target their
supply to particular demands

00:42:17.880 --> 00:42:20.280
and densities.

00:42:20.280 --> 00:42:22.500
A greater involvement
of the private sector.

00:42:22.500 --> 00:42:27.360
So the use of transportation
network companies

00:42:27.360 --> 00:42:28.020
is one example.

00:42:28.020 --> 00:42:31.620
But also partnerships
with the private sector

00:42:31.620 --> 00:42:36.390
to operate bus service, so
public private partnerships.

00:42:36.390 --> 00:42:39.060
And innovative financing
and procurement techniques

00:42:39.060 --> 00:42:44.440
for construction of new
lines or operations.

00:42:44.440 --> 00:42:46.370
Aggressive implementation
of new technology.

00:42:46.370 --> 00:42:50.020
So now, again, I said,
more sensors, more data,

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:51.250
better information provision.

00:42:51.250 --> 00:42:54.640
Tell your customers, your
passengers where the vehicles

00:42:54.640 --> 00:42:56.560
are, what the reliability is.

00:42:56.560 --> 00:42:59.230
Make more effective decisions
like real-time operations

00:42:59.230 --> 00:43:02.320
control to keep your system
operating as you planned it.

00:43:02.320 --> 00:43:05.210
We'll have an entire election
on real-time control later on.

00:43:05.210 --> 00:43:08.150
And you can improve your vehicle
designs-- so all these things,

00:43:08.150 --> 00:43:08.650
right?

00:43:08.650 --> 00:43:10.960
So when I refer to
improve vehicle design,

00:43:10.960 --> 00:43:13.810
we'll talk more about
this in the next lecture.

00:43:13.810 --> 00:43:17.200
We have cleaner technologies,
more fuel efficient,

00:43:17.200 --> 00:43:18.740
more quiet.

00:43:18.740 --> 00:43:22.840
So technology can be used
to improve the experience.

00:43:22.840 --> 00:43:25.990
And then there's the
organizational change.

00:43:25.990 --> 00:43:27.620
So that needs to happen.

00:43:27.620 --> 00:43:30.890
And the public sector is a
little slow in this regard.

00:43:30.890 --> 00:43:35.170
So greater operating staff
responsibility, accountability.

00:43:35.170 --> 00:43:38.170
In many agencies, we have the
problem that it's not clear

00:43:38.170 --> 00:43:40.030
who is responsible for what.

00:43:40.030 --> 00:43:42.400
And so whenever
some decision has

00:43:42.400 --> 00:43:46.390
to be made, who do you
go to get that signature?

00:43:46.390 --> 00:43:47.404
Who approves it?

00:43:47.404 --> 00:43:48.820
You have to talk
to several people

00:43:48.820 --> 00:43:50.310
in different departments.

00:43:50.310 --> 00:43:51.700
And it just gets slow.

00:43:51.700 --> 00:43:53.740
So even for the simple
things, and sometimes

00:43:53.740 --> 00:43:58.140
especially for simple
things, it's a little slow.

00:43:58.140 --> 00:44:00.750
So also increased
customer orientation.

00:44:00.750 --> 00:44:04.360
There's a culture, especially
in the more traditional

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:09.340
public transportation
agencies, that you run service.

00:44:09.340 --> 00:44:13.300
And you don't really think
about people and serving people

00:44:13.300 --> 00:44:15.040
as if they were your customers.

00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:16.690
But that's changing.

00:44:16.690 --> 00:44:19.480
Some agencies, the most
cutting-edge agencies,

00:44:19.480 --> 00:44:22.420
are really treating
people as their customers

00:44:22.420 --> 00:44:26.200
and doing marketing and reaching
out to their customer base

00:44:26.200 --> 00:44:29.770
